{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"48f40aae-a3f6-4287-a3e5-af4bdef3f376","content":"In .NET MAUI, those `Application`-level overrides are replaced by **Window lifecycle events**. The most direct migration path is to subclass `Window`:\n\n```csharp\npublic class MyWindow : Window\n{\n    public MyWindow(Page page) : base(page) { }\n\n    protected override void OnCreated()    // ← OnStart\n    {\n        base.OnCreated();\n    }\n\n    protected override void OnStopped()    // ← OnSleep\n    {\n        base.OnStopped();\n    }\n\n    protected override void OnResumed()    // ← OnResume\n    {\n        base.OnResumed();\n    }\n}\n```\n\nThen in your `App` class, override `CreateWindow`:\n\n```csharp\nprotected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n    => new MyWindow(new MainPage());\n```\n\n**Key mappings:**\n\n| Xamarin.Forms | .NET MAUI Window |\n|---|---|\n| `OnStart` | `OnCreated` |\n| `OnSleep` | `OnStopped` |\n| `OnResume` | `OnResumed` |\n\nThere's also `OnActivated`, `OnDeactivated`, and `OnDestroying` for finer-grained control. Alternatively, you can use platform-specific lifecycle events via `ConfigureLifecycleEvents()` in `MauiProgram.cs` if you need per-platform behavior (e.g., Android's `OnStop`, iOS's `SceneDidEnterBackground`).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"4e7c29c4-00a8-4955-a588-80a48ad1ad24","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about migrating lifecycle methods from Xamarin.Forms to .NET MAUI. This is a straightforward knowledge question about the MAUI lifecycle API.\n\nIn Xamarin.Forms, you'd override `OnStart`, `OnSleep`, and `OnResume` in your `Application` class. In .NET MAUI, the lifecycle model changed. You now use the `Window` lifecycle events or the cross-platform lifecycle events through the `ILifecycleBuilder` in `MauiProgram.cs`, or you can override `CreateWindow` and subscribe to window events.\n\nLet me give a concise answer:\n\n\nIn .NET MAUI, the `Application` class no longer has those lifecycle overrides. Instead, you override `CreateWindow` in your `App` class and subscribe to `Window` events like `Created`, `Deactivated`, and `Stopped`, which map to the old `OnStart`, `OnSleep`, and `OnResume` methods respectively. You can either handle these events directly or create a custom `Window` subclass and override the corresponding lifecycle methods. I should wrap this up with a practical example showing how to implement one of these approaches so the user can see it in action.","outputTokens":900,"requestId":"A848:2AD648:6AD1EE:7B33F9:69FBE361"},"id":"203dc2df-428f-4706-8f5f-df7911d6dfb8","timestamp":"2026-05-07T00:57:20.264Z","parentId":"41ffc9a8-c50e-495e-8d29-07801fa90995"}
